# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rt-thread
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rt-thread/firmware] In computing, **firmware** (**FW**) is software that provides low-level control of computer hardware.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] For a relatively simple device, firmware may perform all control, monitoring and data manipulation functionality.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] For a more complex device, firmware may provide only relatively low-level control as well as hardware abstraction to higher-level software such as an operating system.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Firmware is found in a wide range of computing devices, including personal computers, smartphones, home appliances, vehicles, computer peripherals and in many of the integrated circuits inside each of these larger systems.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Firmware is stored in non-volatile memory – either read-only memory (ROM) or programmable memory such as EPROM, EEPROM, or flash.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Changing a device's firmware stored in ROM requires physically replacing the memory chip or the device itself.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Programmable firmware memory can be reprogrammed via a procedure sometimes called *flashing*.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Common reasons for changing firmware include fixing bugs and adding features.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Ascher Opler used the term *firmware* in a 1967 *Datamation* article, as an intermediary term between *hardware* and *software*.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Opler projected that fourth-generation computer systems would have a writable control store (a small specialized high-speed memory) into which microcode firmware would be loaded.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Many software functions would be moved to microcode, and instruction sets could be customized, with different firmware loaded for different instruction sets.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] As computers began to increase in complexity, it became clear that various programs needed to first be initiated and run to provide a consistent environment necessary for running more complex programs at the user's discretion.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] This required programming the computer to run those programs automatically.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Furthermore, as companies, universities, and marketers wanted to sell computers to laypeople with little technical knowledge, greater automation became necessary to allow a layperson to easily run programs for practical purposes.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] This gave rise to a kind of software that a user would not consciously run, and it led to software that a lay user would not even know about.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] As originally used, firmware contrasted with hardware (the CPU itself) and software (normal instructions executing on a CPU).
[src:rt-thread/firmware] It was not composed of CPU machine instructions, but of lower-level microcode involved in the implementation of machine instructions.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] It existed on the boundary between hardware and software; thus the name *firmware*.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] In some respects, the various firmware components are as important as the operating system in a working computer.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] However, unlike most modern operating systems, firmware rarely has a well-evolved automatic mechanism of updating itself to fix any functionality issues detected after shipping the unit.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] A computer's firmware may be manually updated by a user via a small utility program.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] In contrast, firmware in mass storage devices (hard-disk drives, optical disc drives, flash memory storage e.g., solid state drive) is less frequently updated, even when flash memory (rather than ROM, EEPROM) storage is used for the firmware.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Most computer peripherals are themselves special-purpose computers.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Devices such as printers, scanners, webcams, and USB flash drives have internally-stored firmware; some devices may also permit field upgrading of their firmware.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] For modern, simpler devices, such as USB keyboards, USB mouses and USB sound cards, the trend is to store the firmware in on-chip memory in the device's microcontroller, as opposed to storing it in a separate EEPROM chip.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Consumer products like digital cameras and portable music players support firmware upgrades.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] In digital cameras, firmware upgrades address bugs in the operation, along with adding new functions to the camera's operation.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Some companies use firmware updates to add new playable file formats (codecs).
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Other features that may change with firmware updates include the user interface or even the battery life.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Since 1996, most automobiles have employed an on-board computer and various sensors to detect mechanical problems.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] As of 2010, modern vehicles also employ computer-controlled anti-lock braking systems (ABS) and computer-operated transmission control units (TCUs).
[src:rt-thread/firmware] The driver can also get in-dash information while driving in this manner, such as real-time fuel economy and tire pressure readings.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Local dealers can update most vehicle firmware.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Sometimes, third parties develop an unofficial new or modified ("aftermarket") version of firmware to provide new features or to unlock hidden functionality; this is referred to as custom firmware.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] An example is Rockbox as a firmware replacement for portable media players.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] There are many homebrew projects for various devices, which often unlock general-purpose computing functionality in previously limited devices (e.g., running Doom on iPods).
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Firmware hacks usually take advantage of the firmware update facility on many devices to install or run themselves.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Some, however, must resort to exploits to run, because the manufacturer has attempted to lock the hardware to stop it from running unlicensed code.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Although the Kaspersky Lab report did not explicitly claim that this group is part of the United States National Security Agency (NSA), evidence obtained from the code of various Equation Group software suggests that they are part of the NSA.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Researchers from the Kaspersky Lab categorized the undertakings by Equation Group as the most advanced hacking operation ever uncovered, also documenting around 500 infections caused by the Equation Group in at least 42 countries.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Mark Shuttleworth, the founder of the company Canonical, which created the Ubuntu Linux distribution, has described proprietary firmware as a security risk, saying that "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend" and calling firmware "a trojan horse of monumental proportions".
[src:rt-thread/firmware] As a potential solution to this problem, he has called for declarative firmware, which would describe "hardware linkage and dependencies" and "should not include executable code".
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Firmware should be open-source so that the code can be checked and verified.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Custom firmware hacks have also focused on injecting malware into devices such as smartphones or USB devices.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] One such smartphone injection was demonstrated on the Symbian OS at MalCon, a hacker convention.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] A USB device firmware hack called BadUSB was presented at the Black Hat USA 2014 conference, demonstrating how a USB flash drive microcontroller can be reprogrammed to spoof various other device types to take control of a computer, exfiltrate data, or spy on the user.
[src:rt-thread/firmware] Other security researchers have worked further on how to exploit the principles behind BadUSB, releasing at the same time the source code of hacking tools that can be used to modify the behavior of different USB devices.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The field has evolved due to the convergence of multiple technologies, including ubiquitous computing, sensors, embedded systems, and machine learning.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Traditional fields of embedded systems, wireless sensor networks, control systems, and automation independently and collectively enable the Internet of things.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] While in the consumer market, IoT technology is most commonly as smart home products—including devices and appliances like thermostats and smart speakers—the technology's largest applications are in the business and industrial sectors.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Commercial asset tracking and fleet management represent the largest single application of IoT, accounting for 22% of the total market, driven by the need to monitor mobile assets like vehicles and shipping containers.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The largest asset tracking sub-segments in transport & logistics are trailer and intermodal container tracking, reaching 5.8 million and 5.3 million active devices globally at the end of 2024 respectively.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Other major applications include industrial monitoring, smart metering in utilities, and connected healthcare.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Due to their interconnected nature, IoT devices are vulnerable to security breaches and privacy concerns.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] At the same time, the way these devices communicate wirelessly creates regulatory ambiguities, complicating jurisdictional boundaries of the data transfer.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Around 1972, for its remote site use, the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory developed a computer-controlled vending machine, adapted from a machine rented from Canteen Vending, which sold for cash or, through a computer terminal (Teletype Model 33 KSR), on credit.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Amongst its products were beer, yogurt, and milk.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] It was named *Prancing Pony*, after the name of the room, which was named after an inn in J.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Tolkien's epic fantasy novel The Lord of the Rings.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] A successor version still operates in the Computer Science Department at Stanford, with updated hardware and software.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] While it was initially accessible only on the CMU campus, it gained prominence as the first ARPANET-connected appliance.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Mark Weiser's 1991 paper on ubiquitous computing, "The Computer of the 21st Century", as well as academic venues such as UbiComp and PerCom, produced the contemporary vision of the IoT.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The field gained momentum when Bill Joy envisioned device-to-device communication as part of his "Six Webs" framework, which was presented at the World Economic Forum in Davos in 1999.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The concept of the "Internet of things" and the term itself first appeared in a speech by Peter T.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Lewis to the Congressional Black Caucus Foundation 15th Annual Legislative Weekend in Washington, D.C., published in September 1985.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The primary defining characteristic of the Internet of things has been considered its ability to embed short-range mobile transceivers in various gadgets and daily necessities, enabling new forms of communication between people and things, as well as between things themselves.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Defining the Internet of things as "simply the point in time when more 'things or objects' were connected to the Internet than people", Cisco Systems estimated that the IoT was "born" between 2008 and 2009, with the things/people ratio growing from 0.08 in 2003 to 1.84 in 2010.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The extensive set of applications for IoT devices is often divided into consumer, commercial, industrial, and infrastructure spaces.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] A growing portion of IoT devices is created for consumer use, including connected vehicles, home automation, wearable technology, connected health, and appliances with remote monitoring capabilities.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are part of the broader concept of home automation, which generally includes lighting, heating and air conditioning, media and security systems, and camera systems.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, long-term benefits could include energy savings by automatically ensuring lights and electronics are turned off or by making the residents in the home aware of usage.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] A smart home, also known as an automated home, could be based on a platform or hubs that control smart devices and appliances.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] For instance, using Apple's HomeKit, manufacturers can have their home products and accessories controlled by an application in iOS devices such as the iPhone and the Apple Watch.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] This could be a dedicated app or iOS native applications such as Siri.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] This can be demonstrated in the case of Lenovo's Smart Home Essentials, which is a line of smart home devices that are controlled through Apple's Home app or Siri without the need for a Wi-Fi bridge.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] There are also dedicated smart home hubs that are offered as standalone platforms to connect different smart home products.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] These include the Amazon Echo, Google Home, Apple's HomePod, and Samsung's SmartThings Hub.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to the commercial systems, there are many non-proprietary, open source ecosystems, including Home Assistant, OpenHAB, and Domoticz.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] One key application of a smart home is to assist the elderly and individuals with disabilities.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] These home systems use assistive technology to accommodate an owner's specific disabilities.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Voice control can assist users with sight and mobility limitations while alert systems can be connected directly to cochlear implants worn by individuals with hearing impairments.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] They can also be equipped with additional safety features, including sensors that monitor for medical emergencies such as falls or seizures.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Smart home technology applied in this way can provide users with more freedom and a higher quality of life.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Enterprise IoT" refers to devices used in business and corporate settings.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Medical Things** (**IoMT**) is an application of the IoT for medical and health-related purposes, data collection and analysis for research, and monitoring.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The IoMT has been referenced as "Smart Healthcare", as the technology for creating a digitized healthcare system, connecting available medical resources and healthcare services.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to enable remote health monitoring and emergency notification systems.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] These health monitoring devices can range from blood pressure and heart rate monitors to advanced devices capable of monitoring specialized implants, such as pacemakers, Fitbit electronic wristbands, or advanced hearing aids.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Some hospitals have begun implementing "smart beds" that can detect when they are occupied and when a patient is attempting to get up.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] It can also adjust itself to ensure appropriate pressure and support are applied to the patient without the manual interaction of nurses.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Specialized sensors can also be equipped within living spaces to monitor the health and general well-being of senior citizens, while ensuring that proper treatment is administered and assisting people in regaining lost mobility via therapy as well.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors create a network of intelligent sensors that are able to collect, process, transfer, and analyze valuable information in different environments, such as connecting in-home monitoring devices to hospital-based systems.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Other consumer devices to encourage healthy living, such as connected scales or wearable heart monitors, are also a possibility with the IoT.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] End-to-end health monitoring IoT platforms are also available for antenatal and chronic patients, helping one manage health vitals and recurring medication requirements.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Advances in plastic and fabric electronics fabrication methods have enabled ultra-low-cost, use-and-throw IoMT sensors.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors, along with the required radio-frequency identification electronics, can be fabricated on paper or e-textiles for wireless powered disposable sensing devices.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Applications have been established for point-of-care medical diagnostics, where portability and low system complexity are considered essential.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] As of 2018, IoMT was being applied in the clinical laboratory industry.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoMT in the insurance industry provides access to better and new types of dynamic information.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] This includes sensor-based solutions such as biosensors, wearables, connected health devices, and mobile apps to track customer behavior.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] This can lead to more accurate underwriting and new pricing models.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The application of the IoT in healthcare plays a fundamental role in managing chronic diseases and in disease prevention and control.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Remote monitoring is made possible through the connection of wireless solutions.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The connectivity enables health practitioners to capture patients' data and apply algorithms in health data analysis.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can assist in the integration of communications, control, and information processing across various transportation systems.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Application of the IoT extends to all aspects of transportation systems (i.e., the vehicle, the infrastructure, and the driver or user).
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Dynamic interaction between these components of a transport system enables inter- and intra-vehicular communication, smart traffic control, smart parking, electronic toll collection systems, logistics and fleet management, vehicle control, safety, and road assistance.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicle security applications, IoT-connected GPS trackers can operate for months or years on internal batteries, using low-power wide-area network protocols such as LTE-M to transmit location data to owners via smartphone applications when unauthorized movement is detected.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicular communication systems, vehicle-to-everything communication (V2X), consists of three main components: vehicle-to-vehicle communication (V2V), vehicle-to-infrastructure communication (V2I), and vehicle-to-pedestrian communication (V2P).
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Eventually, V2X is the first step to autonomous driving and connected road infrastructure.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to monitor and control the mechanical, electrical, and electronic systems used in various types of buildings (e.g., public and private, industrial, institutions, or residential) in home automation and building automation systems.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Also known as IIoT, industrial IoT devices acquire and analyze data from connected equipment, operational technology (OT), locations, and people.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Combined with operational technology (OT) monitoring devices, IIoT helps regulate and monitor industrial systems.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, the same implementation can be carried out for automated record updates of asset placement in industrial storage units as the size of the assets can vary from a small screw to the whole motor spare part, and misplacement of such assets can cause a loss of manpower time and money.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can connect various manufacturing devices equipped with sensing, identification, processing, communication, actuation, and networking capabilities.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Network control and management of manufacturing equipment, asset and situation management, or manufacturing process control enable IoT to be utilized for industrial applications and smart manufacturing.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligent systems enable rapid manufacturing and optimization of new products and rapid response to product demands.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Digital control systems, which aim to automate process controls, operator tools, and service information systems, alongside optimizing plant safety and security, fall within the purview of the IIoT.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Furthermore, IoT can also be applied to asset management via predictive maintenance, statistical evaluation, and measurements to maximize reliability.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Industrial management systems can be integrated with smart grids, enabling energy optimization.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Measurements, automated controls, plant optimization, health and safety management, and other functions are provided by networked sensors.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to general manufacturing, IoT is also used for processes in the industrialization of construction.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] There are numerous IoT applications in farming such as collecting data on temperature, rainfall, humidity, wind speed, pest infestation, and soil content.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] This data can be used to automate farming techniques, make informed decisions to improve quality and quantity, minimize risk and waste, and reduce the effort required to manage crops.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] For example, farmers can now monitor soil temperature and moisture from afar and even apply IoT-acquired data to precision fertilization programs.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The overall goal is that data from sensors, coupled with the farmer's knowledge and intuition about his or her farm, can help increase farm productivity, and also help reduce costs.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho began a partnership with Microsoft to create fish farming tools using the Microsoft Azure application suite for IoT technologies related to water management.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Developed in part by researchers from Kindai University, the water pump mechanisms use artificial intelligence to count the number of fish on a conveyor belt, analyze the number of fish, and deduce the effectiveness of water flow from the data the fish provide.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The FarmBeats project from Microsoft Research that uses TV white space to connect farms is also a part of the Azure Marketplace now.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are in use to monitor the environments and systems of boats and yachts.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Many pleasure boats are left unattended for days in summer, and months in winter so such devices provide valuable early alerts of boat flooding, fire, and deep discharge of batteries.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Monitoring and controlling operations of sustainable urban and rural infrastructures like bridges, railway tracks and on- and offshore wind farms is a key application of the IoT.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT infrastructure can be used for monitoring any events or changes in structural conditions that can compromise safety and increase risk.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can benefit the construction industry by cost-saving, time reduction, better quality workday, paperless workflow and increase in productivity.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] It can help in making faster decisions and saving money in Real-Time Data Analytics.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] It can also be used for scheduling repair and maintenance activities efficiently, by coordinating tasks between different service providers and users of these facilities.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can also be used to control critical infrastructure, like bridges, to provide access to ships.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The usage of IoT devices for monitoring and operating infrastructure is likely to significantly improve incident management and emergency response coordination, and quality of service, up-times and reduce costs of operation in all infrastructure-related areas.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Even areas such as waste management can benefit.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] There are several planned or ongoing large-scale deployments of the IoT to enable better management of cities and systems.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] For example, Songdo, South Korea, the first fully equipped and wired smart city, is gradually being built, with approximately 70 percent of the business district completed as of June 2018.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] A sizeable portion of the city, the first of its kind, is planned to be wired and automated to operate with little or no human intervention.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In 2014, another application was undergoing a project in Santander, Spain.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] For this deployment, two approaches have been adopted.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] This city of 180,000 inhabitants has already seen 18,000 downloads of its city smartphone app.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The app is connected to 10,000 sensors that enable services like parking search and environmental monitoring.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, city context information is used in this deployment, aiming to benefit merchants through a spark deals mechanism based on city behavior that aims at maximizing the impact of each notification.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Other examples of large-scale deployments underway include the Sino-Singapore Guangzhou Knowledge City; work on improving air and water quality, reducing noise pollution, and increasing transportation efficiency in San Jose, California; and smart traffic management in western Singapore.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Using its RPMA (Random Phase Multiple Access) technology, San Diego–based Ingenu has built a nationwide public network for low-bandwidth data transmissions using the same unlicensed 2.4 gigahertz spectrum as Wi-Fi.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Ingenu's "Machine Network" covers more than a third of the US population across 35 major cities including San Diego and Dallas.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] French company, Sigfox, commenced building an Ultra Narrowband wireless data network in the San Francisco Bay Area in 2014, the first business to achieve such a deployment in the U.S.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] It subsequently announced it would set up a total of 4000 base stations to cover a total of 30 cities in the U.S. by the end of 2016, making it the largest IoT network coverage provider in the country thus far.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco also participates in smart cities projects.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco has deployed technologies for Smart Wi-Fi, Smart Safety & Security, Smart Lighting, Smart Parking, Smart Transports, Smart Bus Stops, Smart Kiosks, Remote Expert for Government Services (REGS) and Smart Education in the five km area in the city of Vijayawada, India.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of a large deployment is the one completed by New York Waterways in New York City to connect all the city's vessels and be able to monitor them live 24/7.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The network was designed and engineered by Fluidmesh Networks, a Chicago-based company developing wireless networks for critical applications.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The NYWW network is currently providing coverage on the Hudson River, East River, and Upper New York Bay.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] With the wireless network in place, NY Waterway is able to take control of its fleet and passengers in a way that was not previously possible.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] New applications can include security, energy and fleet management, digital signage, public Wi-Fi, paperless ticketing and others.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Significant numbers of energy-consuming devices (e.g., lamps, household appliances, motors, pumps, etc.) already integrate Internet connectivity, which can allow them to communicate with utilities not only to balance power generation but also helps optimize the energy consumption as a whole.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] These devices allow for remote control by users, or central management via a cloud-based interface, and enable functions like scheduling (e.g., remotely powering on or off heating systems, controlling ovens, changing lighting conditions etc.).
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The smart grid is a utility-side IoT application; systems gather and act on energy and power-related information to improve the efficiency of the production and distribution of electricity.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) Internet-connected devices, electric utilities not only collect data from end-users, but also manage distribution automation devices like transformers.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Environmental monitoring applications of the IoT typically use sensors to assist in environmental protection by monitoring air or water quality, atmospheric or soil conditions, and can even include areas like monitoring the movements of wildlife and their habitats.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Development of resource-constrained devices connected to the Internet also means that other applications like earthquake or tsunami early-warning systems can also be used by emergency services to provide more effective aid.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices in this application typically span a large geographic area and can also be mobile.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] It has been argued that the standardization that IoT brings to wireless sensing will revolutionize this area.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of integrating the IoT is the concept of a "living lab." Living labs integrate and combine research and innovation processes, establishing within a public-private-people-partnership.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Between 2006 and January 2024, there were over 440 living labs (though not all are currently active) that use the IoT to collaborate and share knowledge between stakeholders to co-create innovative and technological products.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] When companies intend to implement and develop IoT services for smart cities, they need to have economic incentives.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The US government plays a key role in smart city projects; changes in policies will help cities to implement the IoT, which provides effectiveness, efficiency, and accuracy of the resources that are being used.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The Internet of Military Things (IoMT) is the application of IoT technologies in the military domain for the purposes of reconnaissance, surveillance, and other combat-related objectives.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] It is heavily influenced by the future prospects of warfare in an urban environment and involves the use of sensors, munitions, vehicles, robots, human-wearable biometrics, and other smart technology that is relevant on the battlefield.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] One of the examples of IOT devices used in the military is the Xaver 1000 system.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The Xaver 1000 was developed by Israel's Camero Tech, which is the latest in the company's line of "through-wall imaging systems." The Xaver line uses millimeter wave (MMW) radar, or radar in the range of 30-300 gigahertz.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] It is equipped with an AI-based life target tracking system as well as its own 3D 'sense-through-the-wall' technology.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Battlefield Things** (**IoBT**) is a project initiated and executed by the U.S.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) that focuses on the basic science related to the IoT that enhances the capabilities of Army soldiers.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In 2017, ARL launched the Internet of Battlefield Things Collaborative Research Alliance (IoBT-CRA), establishing a working collaboration between industry, university, and Army researchers to advance the theoretical foundations of IoT technologies and their applications to Army operations.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The **Ocean of Things** project is a DARPA-led program designed to establish an Internet of things across large ocean areas for the purposes of collecting, monitoring, and analyzing environmental and vessel activity data.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The project entails the deployment of about 50,000 floats that house a passive sensor suite that autonomously detects and tracks military and commercial vessels as part of a cloud-based network.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] There are several applications of smart or active packaging in which a QR code or NFC tag is affixed to a product or its packaging.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The tag itself is passive; however, it contains a unique identifier (typically a URL) which enables a user to access digital content about the product via a smartphone.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Strictly speaking, such passive items are not part of the Internet of things, but they can be seen as enablers of digital interactions.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Internet of Packaging" has been coined to describe applications in which unique identifiers are used, to automate supply chains, and are scanned on large scale by consumers to access digital content.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Authentication of the unique identifiers, and thereby of the product itself, is possible via a copy-sensitive digital watermark or copy detection pattern for scanning when scanning a QR code, while NFC tags can encrypt communication.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of Things (IoT), As of April 2026, the number of devices connected and controlled via the Internet has increased.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Applications of IoT technology vary across devices, but many share common characteristics.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT creates opportunities for more direct integration of the physical world into computer-based systems, resulting in efficiency improvements, economic benefits, and reduced human exertions.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT Analytics reported there were 16.6 billion IoT devices connected in 2023.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In 2020, the same firm projected there would be 30 billion devices connected by 2025.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] As of October, 2024, there are around 17 billion.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control are not part of the original concept of the Internet of things.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control do not necessarily require Internet structures, either.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] However, there is a shift in research (by companies such as Intel) to integrate the concepts of the IoT and autonomous control, with initial outcomes towards this direction considering objects as the driving force for autonomous IoT.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] An approach in this context is deep reinforcement learning where most of IoT systems provide a dynamic and interactive environment.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Training an agent (i.e., IoT device) to behave smartly in such an environment cannot be addressed by conventional machine learning algorithms such as supervised learning.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Through a reinforcement learning approach, a learning agent can sense the environment's state (e.g., sensing home temperature), perform actions (e.g., turn HVAC on or off) and learn by maximizing accumulated rewards it receives.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligence can be offered at three levels: IoT devices, Edge/Fog nodes, and cloud computing.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The need for intelligent control and decision at each level depends on the time sensitiveness of the IoT application.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] For example, an autonomous vehicle's camera needs to make real-time obstacle detection to avoid an accident.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] This fast decision making would not be possible if it is necessary to transfer data from the vehicle to cloud instances and return the predictions back to the vehicle.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Instead, the operation should be performed locally in the vehicle.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Integrating advanced machine learning algorithms, including deep learning, into IoT devices is an active research area to make smart objects closer to reality.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, it is possible to get the most value out of IoT deployments through analyzing IoT data, extracting hidden information, and predicting control decisions.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] A wide variety of machine learning techniques have been used in IoT domain ranging from traditional methods such as regression, support vector machine, and random forest to advanced ones such as convolutional neural networks, LSTM, and variational autoencoder.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Modern IoT products and solutions in the marketplace use a variety of different technologies to support such context-aware automation, but more sophisticated forms of intelligence are requested to permit sensor units and intelligent cyber-physical systems to be deployed in real environments.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT system architecture, in its simplistic view, consists of three tiers: Tier 1: Devices, Tier 2: the Edge Gateway, and Tier 3: the Cloud.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Devices include networked things, such as the sensors and actuators found in IoT equipment, particularly those that use protocols such as Modbus, Bluetooth, Zigbee, or proprietary protocols, to connect to an Edge Gateway.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The Edge Gateway layer consists of sensor data aggregation systems called Edge Gateways that provide functionality, such as pre-processing of the data, securing connectivity to cloud, using systems such as WebSockets, the event hub, and, even in some cases, edge analytics or fog computing.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Edge Gateway layer is also required to give a common view of the devices to the upper layers to facilitate in easier management.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The final tier includes the cloud application built for IoT using the microservices architecture, which are usually polyglot and inherently secure in nature using HTTPS/OAuth.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] It includes various database systems that store sensor data, such as time series databases or asset stores using backend data storage systems (e.g.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The cloud tier in most cloud-based IoT system features event queuing and messaging system that handles communication that transpires in all tiers.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Some experts classified the three-tiers in the IoT system as edge, platform, and enterprise and these are connected by proximity network, access network, and service network, respectively.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT requires huge scalability in the network space to handle the surge of devices.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IETF 6LoWPAN can be used to connect devices to IP networks.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] With billions of devices being added to the Internet space, IPv6 may play an important role in handling the network layer scalability.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IETF's Constrained Application Protocol, ZeroMQ, and MQTT can provide lightweight data transport.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In practice, many groups of IoT devices are hidden behind gateway nodes and may not have unique addresses.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Also, the vision of everything being interconnected is not needed for most applications as it is mainly the data that needs interconnecting at a higher layer.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Fog computing is a viable alternative to prevent such a large burst of data flow through the Internet.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The edge devices' computation power to analyze and process data is extremely limited.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Limited processing power is a key attribute of IoT devices as their purpose is to supply data about physical objects while remaining autonomous.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Heavy processing requirements use more battery power, harming IoT's ability to operate.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Scalability is easy because IoT devices simply supply data through the Internet to a server with sufficient processing power.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Performance is improved, especially for huge IoT systems with millions of nodes.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Conventional IoT is connected via a mesh network and led by a major head node (centralized controller).
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The head node decides how a data is created, stored, and transmitted.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In contrast, decentralized IoT attempts to divide IoT systems into smaller divisions.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The head node authorizes partial decision-making power to lower level sub-nodes under mutual agreed policy.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Some approaches to decentralized IoT attempt to address the limited bandwidth and hashing capacity of battery-powered or wireless IoT devices via blockchain.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In semi-open or closed loops (i.e., value chains, whenever a global finality can be settled) the IoT is often analyzed as a complex system due to the large number of different interactions between autonomous actors, and its capacity to integrate new actors.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] At the overall stage (full open loop) it will likely be seen as a chaotic environment (since systems always have finality).
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] As a practical approach, not all elements on the Internet of things run in a global, public space.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Subsystems are often implemented to mitigate the risks of privacy, control and reliability.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] For example, domestic robotics (domotics) running inside a smart home might only share data within and be available via a local network.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Managing and controlling a high dynamic ad hoc IoT things/devices network is a complex task within traditional network architecture, software-defined networking (SDN) provides a dynamic approach that better fits the special requirements of IoT applications.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The exact scale of the Internet of things is unknown, with quotes of billions or trillions often quoted at the beginning of IoT articles.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In 2015, there were 83 million smart devices in people's homes.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] This number is expected to grow to 193 million devices by 2020.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In 2023, the number of connected IoT devices will reach 16.6 billion.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] The number of online-capable devices grew 31% from 2016 to 2017 to reach 8.4 billion.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of things, the precise geographic location of a thing—and also the precise geographic dimensions of a thing—can be critical.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] (Note that some things on the Internet of things will be sensors, and sensor location is usually important.) The GeoWeb and Digital Earth are applications that become possible when things can become organized and connected by location.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] However, the challenges that remain include the constraints of variable spatial scales, the need to handle massive amounts of data, and an indexing for fast search and neighbour operations.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] On the Internet of things, if things are able to take actions on their own initiative, this human-centric mediation role is eliminated.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Thus, the time-space context that we as humans take for granted must be given a central role in this information ecosystem.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Just as standards play a key role on the Internet and the Web, geo-spatial standards will play a key role on the Internet of things.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Many IoT devices have the potential to take a piece of this market.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] For improved user interaction, some technology leaders are joining forces to create standards for communication between devices to solve this problem.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Others are turning to the concept of predictive interaction of devices, "where collected data is used to predict and trigger actions on the specific devices" while making them work together.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Social Internet of things (SIoT) is a new kind of IoT that focuses on the importance of social interaction and relationships between IoT devices.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT defines a device with an identity like a citizen in a community and connects them to the Internet to provide services to its users.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT defines a social network for IoT devices only to interact with each other for different goals that to serve human.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is different from the original IoT in terms of the collaboration characteristics.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT is passive; it was set to serve for dedicated purposes with existing IoT devices in a predetermined system.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is active, it was programmed and managed by AI to serve for unplanned purposes with mix and match of potential IoT devices from different systems that benefit its users.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices with built-in sociability are able to broadcast their abilities or functionality, which can be used to discover and share information with other IoT devices in the same or nearby network, realizing SIoT.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Facilitating further functionality with these abilities could be helpful during emergencies.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] IoT sensors on the vehicles, road and traffic lights monitor the conditions of the vehicles and drivers and alert when attention is needed, and also coordinate themselves automatically to ensure autonomous driving is working normally.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] If a crash happens, the IoT camera will inform the nearest hospital and police station for help.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] System security is always a concern for any technology, and it is more crucial for SIoT as not only the security of oneself needs to be considered, but also the mutual trust mechanism between collaborative IoT devices from time to time, from place to place.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] Another critical challenge for SIoT is the accuracy and reliability of the sensors.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p01] In most circumstances, IoT sensors would need to respond quickly to avoid accidents, injury, and loss of life.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] There are many technologies that enable the IoT.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The original idea of the Auto-ID Center is based on RFID tags and distinct identification through the Electronic Product Code.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] This has evolved into objects having an IP address or URI.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] An alternative view, from the world of the Semantic Web focuses instead on making all things (not just those electronic, smart, or RFID-enabled) addressable by the existing naming protocols, such as URI.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The objects themselves do not converse, but they may now be referred to by other agents, such as powerful centralised servers acting for their human owners.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Integration with the Internet implies that devices will use an IP address as a distinct identifier.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Due to the limited address space of IPv4 (which allows for 4.3 billion different addresses), objects in the IoT will have to use the next generation of the Internet protocol (IPv6) to scale to the extremely large address space required.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Internet-of-things devices additionally will benefit from the stateless address auto-configuration present in IPv6, as it reduces the configuration overhead on the hosts, and the IETF 6LoWPAN header compression.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] To a large extent, the future of the Internet of things will not be possible without the support of IPv6; and consequently, the global adoption of IPv6 in the coming years will be critical for the successful development of the IoT in the future.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Different technologies have different roles in a protocol stack.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] This is a list of technical standards for the IoT, most of which are open standards, and the standards organizations that aspire to successfully setting them.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Some scholars and activists argue that the IoT can be used to create new models of civic engagement if device networks can be open to user control and interoperable platforms.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that political life in both democracies and authoritarian regimes will be shaped by the way the IoT will be used for civic engagement.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] For that to happen, he argues that any connected device should be able to divulge a list of the "ultimate beneficiaries" of its sensor data and that individual citizens should be able to add new organisations to the beneficiary list.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, he argues that civil society groups need to start developing their IoT strategy for making use of data and engaging with the public.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] One of the key drivers of the IoT is data.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The success of the idea of connecting devices to make them more efficient is dependent upon access to and storage & processing of data.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] For this purpose, companies working on the IoT collect data from multiple sources and store it in their cloud network for further processing.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] This leaves the door wide open for privacy and security dangers and single point vulnerability of multiple systems.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The other issues pertain to consumer choice and ownership of data and how it is used.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Though still in their infancy, regulations and governance regarding these issues of privacy, security, and data ownership continue to develop.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Some examples of legislation that is relevant to privacy and data collection are: the US Privacy Act of 1974, OECD Guidelines on the Protection of Privacy and Transborder Flows of Personal Data of 1980, and the EU Directive 95/46/EC of 1995.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] However, the FTC stopped at just making recommendations for now.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] A resolution passed by the Senate in March 2015, is already being considered by the Congress.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] This resolution recognized the need for formulating a National Policy on IoT and the matter of privacy, security and spectrum.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Approved on 28 September 2018, California Senate Bill No.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Several standards for the IoT industry are actually being established relating to automobiles because most concerns arising from use of connected cars apply to healthcare devices as well.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In fact, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) is preparing cybersecurity guidelines and a database of best practices to make automotive computer systems more secure.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] A recent report from the World Bank examines the challenges and opportunities in government adoption of IoT.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In early December 2021, the U.K. government introduced the Product Security and Telecommunications Infrastructure bill (PST), an effort to legislate IoT distributors, manufacturers, and importers to meet certain cybersecurity standards.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The bill also seeks to improve the security credentials of consumer IoT devices.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] For example, wireless connectivity for IoT devices can be done using Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, Wi-Fi HaLow, Zigbee, Z-Wave, LoRa, NB-IoT, Cat M1 as well as completely custom proprietary radios – each with its own advantages and disadvantages; and unique support ecosystem.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The IoT's amorphous computing nature is also a problem for security, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] One set of researchers says that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active Android devices vulnerable.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that the Internet of things offers immense potential for empowering citizens, making government transparent, and broadening information access.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Howard cautions, however, that privacy threats are enormous, as is the potential for social control and political manipulation.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Concerns about privacy have led many to consider the possibility that big data infrastructures such as the Internet of things and data mining are inherently incompatible with privacy.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Key challenges of increased digitalization in the water, transport or energy sector are related to privacy and cybersecurity which necessitate an adequate response from research and policymakers alike.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Writer Adam Greenfield claims that IoT technologies are not only an invasion of public space but are also being used to perpetuate normative behavior, citing an instance of billboards with hidden cameras that tracked the demographics of passersby who stopped to read the advertisement.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Council compared the increased prevalence of digital surveillance due to the Internet of things to the concept of the panopticon described by Jeremy Bentham in the 18th century.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The assertion is supported by the works of French philosophers Michel Foucault and Gilles Deleuze.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In *Discipline and Punish: The Birth of the Prison*, Foucault asserts that the panopticon was a central element of the discipline society developed during the Industrial Era.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Foucault also argued that the discipline systems established in factories and school reflected Bentham's vision of panopticism.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In his 1992 paper "Postscripts on the Societies of Control", Deleuze wrote that the discipline society had transitioned into a control society, with the computer replacing the panopticon as an instrument of discipline and control while still maintaining the qualities similar to that of panopticism.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Peter-Paul Verbeek, a professor of philosophy of technology at the University of Twente, Netherlands, writes that technology already influences our moral decision making, which in turn affects human agency, privacy and autonomy.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] He cautions against viewing technology merely as a human tool and advocates instead to consider it as an active agent.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Tim O'Reilly believes that the way companies sell IoT devices to consumers is misplaced, disputing the notion that the IoT is about gaining efficiency from putting all kinds of devices online and postulating that, "IoT is really about human augmentation.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Editorials at WIRED have also expressed concern, one stating, "What you're about to lose is your privacy.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) expressed concern regarding the ability of IoT to erode people's control over their own lives.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The ACLU wrote that "There's simply no way to forecast how these immense powers – disproportionately accumulating in the hands of corporations seeking financial advantage and governments craving ever more control – will be used.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In response to rising concerns about privacy and smart technology, in 2007, the British Government stated it would follow formal Privacy by Design principles when implementing its smart metering program.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The program would lead to the replacement of traditional power meters with smart power meters, which could track and manage energy usage more accurately.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] However the British Computer Society is doubtful these principles were ever actually implemented.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In 2009, the Dutch Parliament rejected a similar smart metering program, basing their decision on privacy concerns.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The Dutch program later revised and passed in 2011.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] A challenge for producers of IoT applications is to clean, process and interpret the vast amount of data that is gathered by the sensors.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] There is a solution proposed for the analytics of the information referred to as Wireless Sensor Networks.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] These networks share data among sensor nodes that are sent to a distributed system for the analytics of the sensory data.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Another challenge is the storage of this bulk data.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Depending on the application, there could be high data acquisition requirements, which in turn lead to high storage requirements.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In 2013, the Internet was estimated to be responsible for consuming 5% of the total energy produced, and a "daunting challenge to power" IoT devices to collect and even store data still remains.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Data silos, although a common challenge of legacy systems, still commonly occur with the implementation of IoT devices, particularly within manufacturing.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] As there are a lot of benefits to be gained from IoT and IIoT devices, the means in which the data is stored can present serious challenges without the principles of autonomy, transparency, and interoperability being considered.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The challenges do not occur by the device itself, but the means in which databases and data warehouses are set up.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] These challenges were identified by Keller (2021) when investigating the IT and application landscape of I4.0 implementation within German M&E manufacturers.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Security is the biggest concern in adopting Internet of things technology, with concerns that rapid development is happening without appropriate consideration of the profound security challenges involved and the regulatory changes that might be necessary.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The rapid development of the Internet of Things (IoT) has allowed billions of devices to connect to the network.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Due to too many connected devices and the limitation of communication security technology, various security issues gradually appear in the IoT.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Most of the technical security concerns are similar to those of conventional servers, workstations and smartphones.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] These concerns include using weak authentication, forgetting to change default credentials, unencrypted messages sent between devices, SQL injections, man-in-the-middle attacks, and poor handling of security updates.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] However, many IoT devices have severe operational limitations on the computational power available to them.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] These constraints often make them unable to directly use basic security measures such as implementing firewalls or using strong cryptosystems to encrypt their communications with other devices - and the low price and consumer focus of many devices makes a robust security patching system uncommon.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Rather than conventional security vulnerabilities, fault injection attacks are on the rise and targeting IoT devices.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] A fault injection attack is a physical attack on a device to purposefully introduce faults in the system to change the intended behavior.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Faults might happen unintentionally due to environmental noises and electromagnetic fields.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] There are ideas stemming from control-flow integrity (CFI) to prevent fault injection attacks and system recovery to a healthy state before the fault.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Computer-controlled devices in automobiles such as brakes, engine, locks, hood and trunk releases, horn, heat, and dashboard have been shown to be vulnerable to attackers who have access to the on-board network.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In some cases, vehicle computer systems are Internet-connected, allowing them to be exploited remotely.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] By 2008, security researchers had shown the ability to remotely control pacemakers without authority.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Later, hackers demonstrated remote control of insulin pumps and implantable cardioverter defibrillators.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Poorly secured Internet-accessible IoT devices can also be subverted to attack others.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In 2016, a distributed denial of service attack powered by Internet of things devices running the Mirai malware took down a DNS provider and major web sites.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had infected roughly 65,000 IoT devices within the first 20 hours.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Eventually, the infections increased to around 200,000 to 300,000 infections.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Brazil, Colombia and Vietnam made up of 41.5% of the infections.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had singled out specific IoT devices that consisted of DVRs, IP cameras, routers and printers.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] These sorts of attacks have caused security experts to view IoT as a real threat to Internet services.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] National Intelligence Council in an unclassified report maintains that it would be hard to deny "access to networks of sensors and remotely-controlled objects by enemies of the United States, criminals, and mischief makers...
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] An open market for aggregated sensor data could serve the interests of commerce and security no less than it helps criminals and spies identify vulnerable targets.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Thus, massively parallel sensor fusion may undermine social cohesion, if it proves to be fundamentally incompatible with Fourth-Amendment guarantees against unreasonable search." In general, the intelligence community views the Internet of things as a rich source of data.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] There have been a range of responses to concerns over security.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Security Foundation (IoTSF) was launched on 23 September 2015 with a mission to secure the Internet of things by promoting knowledge and best practices.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Its founding board is made up of technology providers and telecommunications companies.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, large IT companies are continually developing innovative solutions to ensure the security of IoT devices.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In 2017, Mozilla launched Project Things, which allows to route IoT devices through a safe Web of Things gateway.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] As per the estimates from KBV Research, the overall IoT security market would grow at 27.9% rate during 2016–2022 as a result of growing infrastructural concerns and diversified usage of Internet of things.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Governmental regulation is argued by some to be necessary to secure IoT devices and the wider Internet – as market incentives to secure IoT devices is insufficient.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] It was found that due to the nature of most of the IoT development boards, they generate predictable and weak keys which make it easy to be utilized by man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] However, various hardening approaches were proposed by many researchers to resolve the issue of SSH weak implementation and weak keys.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] IoT security within the field of manufacturing presents different challenges and varying perspectives.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Within the EU and Germany, data protection is constantly referenced throughout manufacturing and digital policy, particularly that of I4.0.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] However, the attitude towards data security differs from the enterprise perspective, whereas there is an emphasis on less data protection in the form of GDPR, as the data being collected from IoT devices in the manufacturing sector does not display personal details.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Yet, research has indicated that manufacturing experts are concerned about "data security for protecting machine technology from international competitors with the ever-greater push for interconnectivity".
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] IoT systems are typically controlled by event-driven smart apps that take as input either sensed data, user inputs, or other external triggers (from the Internet) and command one or more actuators towards providing different forms of automation.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of sensors include smoke detectors, motion sensors, and contact sensors.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of actuators include smart locks, smart power outlets, and door controls.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Popular control platforms on which third-party developers can build smart apps that interact wirelessly with these sensors and actuators include Samsung's SmartThings, Apple's HomeKit, and Amazon's Alexa, among others.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Detecting flaws that lead to such states, requires a holistic view of installed apps, component devices, their configurations, and more importantly, how they interact.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Recently, researchers from the University of California Riverside have proposed IotSan, a novel practical system that uses model checking as a building block to reveal "interaction-level" flaws by identifying events that can lead the system to unsafe states.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] They have evaluated IotSan on the Samsung SmartThings platform.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] From 76 manually configured systems, IotSan detects 147 vulnerabilities (i.e., violations of safe physical states/properties).
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Given widespread recognition of the evolving nature of the design and management of the Internet of things, sustainable and secure deployment of IoT solutions must design for "anarchic scalability".
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Application of the concept of anarchic scalability can be extended to physical systems (i.e. controlled real-world objects), by virtue of those systems being designed to account for uncertain management futures.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] This hard anarchic scalability thus provides a pathway forward to fully realize the potential of Internet-of-things solutions by selectively constraining physical systems to allow for all management regimes without risking physical failure.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Brown University computer scientist Michael Littman has argued that successful execution of the Internet of things requires consideration of the interface's usability as well as the technology itself.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] A concern regarding Internet-of-things technologies pertains to the environmental impacts of the manufacture, use, and eventual disposal of all these semiconductor-rich devices.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Modern electronics are replete with a wide variety of heavy metals and rare-earth metals, as well as highly toxic synthetic chemicals.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] This makes them extremely difficult to properly recycle.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Electronic components are often incinerated or placed in regular landfills.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Furthermore, the human and environmental cost of mining the rare-earth metals that are integral to modern electronic components continues to grow.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] This leads to societal questions concerning the environmental impacts of IoT devices over their lifetime.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The Electronic Frontier Foundation has raised concerns that companies can use the technologies necessary to support connected devices to intentionally disable or "brick" their customers' devices via a remote software update or by disabling a service necessary to the operation of the device.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In one example, home automation devices sold with the promise of a "Lifetime Subscription" were rendered useless after Nest Labs acquired Revolv and made the decision to shut down the central servers the Revolv devices had used to operate.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Owners should be free to point their devices to a different server or collaborate on improved software.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] But such action violates the United States DMCA section 1201, which only has an exemption for "local use".
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] This forces tinkerers who want to keep using their own equipment into a legal grey area.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] EFF thinks buyers should refuse electronics and software that prioritize the manufacturer's wishes above their own.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of post-sale manipulations include Google Nest Revolv, disabled privacy settings on Android, Sony disabling Linux on PlayStation 3, and enforced EULA on Wii U.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Kevin Lonergan at *Information Age*, a business technology magazine, has referred to the terms surrounding the IoT as a "terminology zoo".
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The lack of clear terminology is not "useful from a practical point of view" and a "source of confusion for the end user".
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] A company operating in the IoT space could be working in anything related to sensor technology, networking, embedded systems, or analytics.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Regarding IIoT, an industrial sub-field of IoT, the Industrial Internet Consortium's Vocabulary Task Group has created a "common and reusable vocabulary of terms" to ensure "consistent terminology" across publications issued by the Industrial Internet Consortium.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] IoT One has created an IoT Terms Database including a New Term Alert to be notified when a new term is published.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] As of March 2020, this database aggregates 807 IoT-related terms, while keeping material "transparent and comprehensive".
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Despite a shared belief in the potential of the IoT, industry leaders and consumers are facing barriers to adopting IoT technology more widely.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Mike Farley argued in Forbes that while IoT solutions appeal to early adopters, they either lack interoperability or a clear use case for end-users.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] A study by Ericsson regarding the adoption of IoT among Danish companies suggests that many struggle "to pinpoint exactly where the value of IoT lies for them".
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] As for IoT, especially in regard to consumer IoT, information about a user's daily routine is collected so that the "things" around the user can cooperate to provide better services that fulfill personal preferences.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] When the collected information which describes a user in detail travels through multiple hops in a network, due to a diverse integration of services, devices and network, the information stored on a device is vulnerable to privacy violation by compromising nodes existing in an IoT network.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] For example, on 21 October 2016, a multiple distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks systems operated by domain name system provider Dyn, which caused the inaccessibility of several websites, such as GitHub, Twitter, and others.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] This attack is executed through a botnet consisting of a large number of IoT devices including IP cameras, gateways, and even baby monitors.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Information privacy regulations also require organisations to practice "reasonable security".
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] As each organisation's environment is unique, it can prove challenging to demonstrate what "reasonable security" is and what potential risks could be involved for the business.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] According to antivirus provider Kaspersky, there were 639 million data breaches of IoT devices in 2020 and 1.5 billion breaches in the first six months of 2021.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] One method of overcoming the barrier of safety issues is the introduction of standards and certification of devices.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] In 2024, two voluntary and non-competing programs were proposed and launched in the United States: the US Cyber Trust Mark from The Federal Communications Commission and CSA's IoT Device Security Specification from the Connectivity Standards Alliance.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] The programs incorporate international expertise, with the CSA mark recognized by the Singapore Cybersecurity Agency.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Compliance means that IoT devices can resist hacking, control hijacking and theft of confidential data.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Some of these companies risk being "kodaked" – "Kodak was a market leader until digital disruption eclipsed film photography with digital photos" – failing to "see the disruptive forces affecting their industry" and "to truly embrace the new business models the disruptive change opens up".
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] According to a 2018 study, 70–75% of IoT deployments were stuck in the pilot or prototype stage, unable to reach scale due in part to a lack of business planning.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Even though scientists, engineers, and managers across the world are continuously working to create and exploit the benefits of IoT products, there are some flaws in the governance, management and implementation of such projects.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Despite tremendous forward momentum in the field of information and other underlying technologies, IoT still remains a complex area and the problem of how IoT projects are managed still needs to be addressed.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] IoT projects must be run differently than simple and traditional IT, manufacturing or construction projects.
[src:rt-thread/internet-of-things-p02] Because IoT projects have longer project timelines, a lack of skilled resources and several security/legal issues, there is a need for new and specifically designed project processes.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A **microcontroller** (**MC**, **uC**, or **μC**) or **microcontroller unit** (**MCU**) is a small computer on a single integrated circuit.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A microcontroller contains one or more processor cores along with memory and programmable input/output peripherals.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Program memory in the form of NOR flash, OTP ROM, or ferroelectric RAM is also often included on the chip, as well as a small amount of RAM.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are designed for embedded applications, in contrast to the microprocessors used in personal computers or other general-purpose applications consisting of various discrete chips.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] In modern terminology, a microcontroller is similar to, but less sophisticated than, a system on a chip (SoC).
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A SoC may include a microcontroller as one of its components but usually integrates it with advanced peripherals like a graphics processing unit (GPU), a Wi-Fi module, or one or more coprocessors.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are used in automatically controlled products and devices, such as automobile engine control systems, implantable medical devices, remote controls, office machines, appliances, power tools, toys, and other embedded systems.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] By reducing the size and cost compared to a design that uses a separate microprocessor, memory, and input/output devices, microcontrollers make digital control of more devices and processes practical.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Mixed-signal microcontrollers are common, integrating analog components needed to control non-digital electronic systems.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] In the context of the Internet of things, microcontrollers are an economical and popular means of data collection, sensing and actuating the physical world as edge devices.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers may use four-bit words and operate at frequencies as low as 4 kHz for low power consumption (single-digit milliwatts or microwatts).
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] They generally have the ability to retain functionality while waiting for an event such as a button press or other interrupt; power consumption while sleeping (with the CPU clock and most peripherals off) may be just nanowatts, making many of them well suited for long lasting battery applications.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Other microcontrollers may serve performance-critical roles, where they may need to act more like a digital signal processor (DSP), with higher clock speeds and power consumption.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released on a single MOS LSI chip in 1971.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] It was followed by the 4-bit Intel 4040, the 8-bit Intel 8008, and the 8-bit Intel 8080.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] All of these processors required several external chips to implement a working system, including memory and peripheral interface chips.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] As a result, the total system cost was several hundred (1970s US) dollars, making it impossible to economically computerize small appliances.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] MOS Technology introduced its sub-$100 microprocessors in 1975, the 6501 and 6502.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Their chief aim was to reduce this cost barrier but these microprocessors still required external support, memory, and peripheral chips which kept the total system cost in the hundreds of dollars.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] One book credits TI engineers Gary Boone and Michael Cochran with the successful creation of the first microcontroller in 1971.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] The result of their work was the TMS 1000, which became commercially available in 1974.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] It combined read-only memory, read/write memory, processor and clock on one chip and was targeted at embedded systems.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] During the early-to-mid-1970s, Japanese electronics manufacturers began producing microcontrollers for automobiles, including 4-bit MCUs for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, and dashboard, and 8-bit MCUs for engine control.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Partly in response to the existence of the single-chip TMS 1000, Intel developed a computer system on a chip optimized for control applications, the Intel 8048, with commercial parts first shipping in 1977.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] It combined RAM and ROM on the same chip with a microprocessor.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Among numerous applications, this chip would eventually find its way into over one billion PC keyboards.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Valenter, stated that the microcontroller was one of the most successful products in the company's history, and he expanded the microcontroller division's budget by over 25%.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Most microcontrollers at this time had concurrent variants.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] One had EPROM program memory, with a transparent quartz window in the lid of the package to allow it to be erased by exposure to ultraviolet light.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] These erasable chips were often used for prototyping.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] The other variant was either a mask-programmed ROM or a PROM variant which was only programmable once.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] For the latter, sometimes the designation *OTP* was used, standing for "one-time programmable".
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] In an OTP microcontroller, the PROM was usually of identical type as the EPROM, but the chip package had no quartz window; because there was no way to expose the EPROM to ultraviolet light, it could not be erased.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Because the erasable versions required ceramic packages with quartz windows, they were significantly more expensive than the OTP versions, which could be made in lower-cost opaque plastic packages.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] For the erasable variants, quartz was required, instead of less expensive glass, for its transparency to ultraviolet light—to which glass is largely opaque—but the main cost differentiator was the ceramic package itself.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] **Piggyback microcontrollers** were also used.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] In 1993, the introduction of EEPROM memory allowed microcontrollers (beginning with the Microchip PIC16C84) to be electrically erased quickly without an expensive package as required for EPROM, allowing both rapid prototyping, and in-system programming.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] (EEPROM technology had been available prior to this time, but the earlier EEPROM was more expensive and less durable, making it unsuitable for low-cost mass-produced microcontrollers.) The same year, Atmel introduced the first microcontroller using Flash memory, a special type of EEPROM.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Other companies rapidly followed suit, with both memory types.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Nowadays microcontrollers are cheap and readily available for hobbyists, with large online communities around certain processors.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] In 2002, about 55% of all CPUs sold in the world were 8-bit microcontrollers and microprocessors.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Over two billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 1997, and according to Semico, over four billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 2006.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] More recently, Semico has claimed the MCU market grew 36.5% in 2010 and 12% in 2011.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A typical home in a developed country is likely to have only four general-purpose microprocessors but around three dozen microcontrollers.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A typical mid-range automobile has about 30 microcontrollers.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] They can also be found in many electrical devices such as washing machines, microwave ovens, and telephones.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Cost to manufacture can be under US$0.10 per unit.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Cost has plummeted over time, with the cheapest 8-bit microcontrollers being available for under US$0.03 in 2018, and some 32-bit microcontrollers around US$1 for similar quantities.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] In 2012, following a global crisis—a worst ever annual sales decline and recovery and average sales price year-over-year plunging 17%—the biggest reduction since the 1980s—the average price for a microcontroller was US$0.88 (US$0.69 for 4-/8-bit, US$0.59 for 16-bit, US$1.76 for 32-bit).
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] In 2012, worldwide sales of 8-bit microcontrollers were around US$4 billion, while 4-bit microcontrollers also saw significant sales.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] On 21 June 2018, the "world's smallest computer" was announced by the University of Michigan.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Because they are too small to have conventional radio antennae, they receive and transmit data with visible light.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A microcontroller can be considered a self-contained system with a processor, memory and peripherals and can be used as an embedded system.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] The majority of microcontrollers in use today are embedded in other machinery, such as automobiles, telephones, appliances, and peripherals for computer systems.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] While some embedded systems are very sophisticated, many have minimal requirements for memory and program length, with no operating system, and low software complexity.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Typical input and output devices include switches, relays, solenoids, LEDs, small or custom liquid-crystal displays, radio frequency devices, and sensors for data such as temperature, humidity, light level etc.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Embedded systems usually have no keyboard, screen, disks, printers, or other recognizable I/O devices of a personal computer, and may lack human interaction devices of any kind.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Microcontrollers must provide real-time (predictable, though not necessarily fast) response to events in the embedded system they are controlling.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Possible interrupt sources are device-dependent and often include events such as an internal timer overflow, completing an analog-to-digital conversion, a logic-level change on an input such as from a button being pressed, and data received on a communication link.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Where power consumption is important as in battery devices, interrupts may also wake a microcontroller from a low-power sleep state where the processor is halted until required to do something by a peripheral event.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Typically microcontroller programs must fit in the available on-chip memory, since it would be costly to provide a system with external, expandable memory.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Compilers and assemblers are used to convert both high-level and assembly language code into a compact machine code for storage in the microcontroller's memory.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Depending on the device, the program memory may be permanent, read-only memory that can only be programmed at the factory, or it may be field-alterable flash or erasable read-only memory.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Manufacturers have often produced special versions of their microcontrollers in order to help the hardware and software development of the target system.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Originally these included EPROM versions that have a "window" on the top of the device through which program memory can be erased by ultraviolet light, ready for reprogramming after a programming ("burn") and test cycle.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Since 1998, EPROM versions are rare and have been replaced by EEPROM and flash, which are easier to use (can be erased electronically) and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Other versions may be available where the ROM is accessed as an external device rather than as internal memory, however these are becoming rare due to the widespread availability of cheap microcontroller programmers.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] The use of field-programmable devices on a microcontroller may allow field update of the firmware or permit late factory revisions to products that have been assembled but not yet shipped.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Programmable memory also reduces the lead time required for deployment of a new product.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Where hundreds of thousands of identical devices are required, using parts programmed at the time of manufacture can be economical.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] These "mask-programmed" parts have the program laid down in the same way as the logic of the chip, at the same time.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A customized microcontroller incorporates a block of digital logic that can be personalized for additional processing capability, peripherals and interfaces that are adapted to the requirements of the application.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Microcontrollers usually contain from several to dozens of general purpose input/output pins (GPIO).
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] GPIO pins are software configurable to either an input or an output state.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] When GPIO pins are configured to an input state, they are often used to read sensors or external signals.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Configured to the output state, GPIO pins can drive external devices such as LEDs or motors, often indirectly, through external power electronics.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Many embedded systems need to read sensors that produce analog signals.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] However, because they are built to interpret and process digital data, i.e.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] 1s and 0s, they are not able to do anything with the analog signals that may be sent to it by a device.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] So, an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) is used to convert the incoming data into a form that the processor can recognize.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A less common feature on some microcontrollers is a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) that allows the processor to output analog signals or voltage levels.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] In addition to the converters, many embedded microprocessors include a variety of timers as well.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] One of the most common types of timers is the programmable interval timer (PIT).
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A PIT may either count down from some value to zero, or up to the capacity of the count register, overflowing to zero.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Once it reaches zero, it sends an interrupt to the processor indicating that it has finished counting.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] This is useful for devices such as thermostats, which periodically test the temperature around them to see if they need to turn the air conditioner on/off, the heater on/off, etc.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A dedicated pulse-width modulation (PWM) block makes it possible for the CPU to control power converters, resistive loads, motors, etc., without using many CPU resources in tight timer loops.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A universal asynchronous receiver/transmitter (UART) block makes it possible to receive and transmit data over a serial line with very little load on the CPU.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Dedicated on-chip hardware also often includes capabilities to communicate with other devices (chips) in digital formats such as Inter-Integrated Circuit (I²C), Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI), Universal Serial Bus (USB), and Ethernet.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Microcontrollers may not implement an external address or data bus as they integrate RAM and non-volatile memory on the same chip as the CPU.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Using fewer pins, the chip can be placed in a much smaller, cheaper package.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Integrating the memory and other peripherals on a single chip and testing them as a unit increases the cost of that chip, but often results in decreased net cost of the embedded system as a whole.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] This integration drastically reduces the number of chips and the amount of wiring and circuit board space that would be needed to produce equivalent systems using separate chips.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Furthermore, on low pin count devices in particular, each pin may interface to several internal peripherals, with the pin function selected by software.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] This allows a part to be used in a wider variety of applications than if pins had dedicated functions.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Microcontrollers have proved to be highly popular in embedded systems since their introduction in the 1970s.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers use a Harvard architecture: separate memory buses for instructions and data, allowing accesses to take place concurrently.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Where a Harvard architecture is used, instruction words for the processor may be a different bit size than the length of internal memory and registers; for example: 12-bit instructions used with 8-bit data registers.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] The decision of which peripheral to integrate is often difficult.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] The microcontroller vendors often trade operating frequencies and system design flexibility against time-to-market requirements from their customers and overall lower system cost.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Manufacturers have to balance the need to minimize the chip size against additional functionality.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Microcontroller architectures vary widely.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Some designs include general-purpose microprocessor cores, with one or more ROM, RAM, or I/O functions integrated onto the package.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Other designs are purpose-built for control applications.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A microcontroller instruction set usually has many instructions intended for bit manipulation (bit-wise operations) to make control programs more compact.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] For example, a general-purpose processor might require several instructions to test a bit in a register and branch if the bit is set, where a microcontroller could have a single instruction to provide that commonly required function.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Microcontrollers historically have not had math coprocessors, so floating-point arithmetic has been performed by software.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] However, some recent designs do include FPUs and DSP-optimized features.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] An example would be Microchip's PIC32 MIPS-based line.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Microcontrollers were originally programmed only in assembly language, but various high-level programming languages, such as C, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Compilers for general-purpose languages will typically have some restrictions as well as enhancements to better support the unique characteristics of microcontrollers.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers have environments to aid developing certain types of applications.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Microcontroller vendors often make tools freely available to make it easier to adopt their hardware.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Microcontrollers with specialty hardware may require their own non-standard dialects of C, such as SDCC for the 8051, which prevent using standard tools (such as code libraries or static analysis tools) even for code unrelated to hardware features.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Interpreters may also contain nonstandard features, such as MicroPython, although a fork, CircuitPython, has looked to move hardware dependencies to libraries and have the language adhere to a more CPython standard.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Interpreter firmware is also available for some microcontrollers.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] For example, BASIC on the early microcontroller Intel 8052; BASIC and FORTH on the Zilog Z8 as well as some modern devices.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Typically these interpreters support interactive programming.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Simulators are available for some microcontrollers.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] These allow a developer to analyze what the behavior of the microcontroller and their program should be if they were using the actual part.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A simulator will show the internal processor state and also that of the outputs, as well as allowing input signals to be generated.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] While on the one hand most simulators will be limited from being unable to simulate much other hardware in a system, they can exercise conditions that may otherwise be hard to reproduce at will in the physical implementation, and can be the quickest way to debug and analyze problems.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Recent microcontrollers are often integrated with on-chip debug circuitry that when accessed by an in-circuit emulator (ICE) via JTAG, allow debugging of the firmware with a debugger.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A real-time ICE may allow viewing and/or manipulating of internal states while running.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A tracing ICE can record executed program and MCU states before/after a trigger point.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Many others exist, some of which are used in very narrow range of applications or are more like applications processors than microcontrollers.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] The microcontroller market is extremely fragmented, with numerous vendors, technologies, and markets.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Note that many vendors sell or have sold multiple architectures.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] In contrast to general-purpose computers, microcontrollers used in embedded systems often seek to optimize interrupt latency over instruction throughput.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Issues include both reducing the latency, and making it be more predictable (to support real-time control).
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] When an electronic device causes an interrupt, during the context switch the intermediate results (registers) have to be saved before the software responsible for handling the interrupt can run.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] They must also be restored after that interrupt handler is finished.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] If there are more processor registers, this saving and restoring process may take more time, increasing the latency.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Another technique involves spending silicon gates on "shadow registers": One or more duplicate registers used only by the interrupt software, perhaps supporting a dedicated stack.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Lower end microcontrollers tend to support fewer interrupt latency controls than higher end ones.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Two different kinds of memory are commonly used with microcontrollers, a non-volatile memory for storing firmware and a read–write memory for temporary data.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] From the earliest microcontrollers to today, six-transistor SRAM is almost always used as the read/write working memory, with a few more transistors per bit used in the register file.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] In addition to the SRAM, some microcontrollers also have internal EEPROM and/or NVRAM for data storage; and ones that do not have any (such as the BASIC Stamp), or where the internal memory is insufficient, are often connected to an external EEPROM or flash memory chip.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] A few microcontrollers beginning in 2003 have "self-programmable" flash memory.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] The earliest microcontrollers used mask ROM to store firmware.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Later microcontrollers (such as the early versions of the Freescale 68HC11 and early PIC microcontrollers) had EPROM memory, which used a translucent window to allow erasure via UV light, while production versions had no such window, being OTP (one-time-programmable).
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Firmware updates were equivalent to replacing the microcontroller itself, thus many products were not upgradeable.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Motorola MC68HC805 was the first microcontroller to use EEPROM to store the firmware.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] EEPROM microcontrollers became more popular in 1993 when Microchip introduced PIC16C84 and Atmel introduced an 8051-core microcontroller that was first one to use NOR Flash memory to store the firmware.
[src:rt-thread/microcontroller] Today's microcontrollers almost all use flash memory, with a few models using FRAM and some ultra-low-cost parts still using OTP or mask ROM.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] A **real-time operating system** (**RTOS**) is an operating system (OS) for real-time computing applications that processes data and events that have critically defined time constraints.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS mainly targets resource constrained devices like microcontrollers.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] It is distinct from a time-sharing operating system, such as Unix, which manages the sharing of system resources with a scheduler, data buffers, or fixed task prioritization in multitasking or multiprogramming environments.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] All operations must verifiably complete within given time and resource constraints or else the RTOS will fail safe.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Real-time operating systems are event-driven and preemptive, meaning the OS can monitor the relevant priority of competing tasks, and make changes to the task priority.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] A key characteristic of an RTOS is the level of its consistency concerning the amount of time it takes to accept and complete an application's task; the variability is "jitter".
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The chief design goal is not high throughput, but rather a guarantee of a soft or hard performance category.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS that can usually or generally meet a deadline is a soft real-time OS, but if it can meet a deadline deterministically it is a hard real-time OS.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS has an advanced algorithm for scheduling.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Scheduler flexibility enables a wider, computer-system orchestration of process priorities, but a real-time OS is more frequently dedicated to a narrow set of applications.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Key factors in a real-time OS are minimal interrupt latency and minimal thread switching latency; a real-time OS is valued more for how quickly or how predictably it can respond than for the amount of work it can perform in a given period of time.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Time sharing designs switch tasks more often than strictly needed, but give smoother multitasking, giving the illusion that a process or user has sole use of a machine.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Early CPU designs needed many cycles to switch tasks during which the CPU could do nothing else useful.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Because switching took so long, early OSes tried to minimize wasting CPU time by avoiding unnecessary task switching.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Blocked (waiting for an event, I/O for example).
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Most tasks are blocked or ready most of the time because generally only one task can run at a time per CPU core.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The number of items in the ready queue can vary greatly, depending on the number of tasks the system needs to perform and the type of scheduler that the system uses.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] On simpler non-preemptive but still multitasking systems, a task has to give up its time on the CPU to other tasks, which can cause the ready queue to have a greater number of overall tasks in the ready to be executed state (resource starvation).
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] If there are never more than a few tasks on the ready list, then a doubly linked list of ready tasks is likely optimal.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] If the ready list usually contains only a few tasks but occasionally contains more, then the list should be sorted by priority, so that finding the highest priority task to run does not require traversing the list.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Instead, inserting a task requires walking the list.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] During this search, preemption should not be inhibited.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Long critical sections should be divided into smaller pieces.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] If an interrupt occurs that makes a high priority task ready during the insertion of a low priority task, that high priority task can be inserted and run immediately before the low priority task is inserted.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The critical response time, sometimes called the flyback time, is the time it takes to queue a new ready task and restore the state of the highest priority task to running.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] In a well-designed RTOS, readying a new task will take 3 to 20 instructions per ready-queue entry, and restoration of the highest-priority ready task will take 5 to 30 instructions.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] In advanced systems, real-time tasks share computing resources with many non-real-time tasks, and the ready list can be arbitrarily long.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] In such systems, a scheduler ready list implemented as a linked list would be inadequate.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] A multitasking operating system like Unix is poor at real-time tasks.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The scheduler gives the highest priority to jobs with the lowest demand on the computer, so there is no way to ensure that a time-critical job will have access to enough resources.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Multitasking systems must manage sharing data and hardware resources among multiple tasks.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] It is usually unsafe for two tasks to access the same specific data or hardware resource simultaneously.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] General-purpose operating systems usually do not allow user programs to mask (disable) interrupts, because the user program could control the CPU for as long as it is made to.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Some modern CPUs do not allow user mode code to disable interrupts as such control is considered a key operating system resource.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Many embedded systems and RTOSs, however, allow the application itself to run in kernel mode for greater system call efficiency and also to permit the application to have greater control of the operating environment without requiring OS intervention.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] On single-processor systems, an application running in kernel mode and masking interrupts is the lowest overhead method to prevent simultaneous access to a shared resource.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] While interrupts are masked and the current task does not make a blocking OS call, the current task has *exclusive* use of the CPU since no other task or interrupt can take control, so the critical section is protected.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] When the task exits its critical section, it must unmask interrupts; pending interrupts, if any, will then execute.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Temporarily masking interrupts should only be done when the longest path through the critical section is shorter than the desired maximum interrupt latency.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Typically this method of protection is used only when the critical section is just a few instructions and contains no loops.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] This method is ideal for protecting hardware bit-mapped registers when the bits are controlled by different tasks.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] When the shared resource must be reserved without blocking all other tasks (such as waiting for Flash memory to be written), it is better to use mechanisms also available on general-purpose operating systems, such as a mutex and OS-supervised interprocess messaging.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Such mechanisms involve system calls, and usually invoke the OS's dispatcher code on exit, so they typically take hundreds of CPU instructions to execute, while masking interrupts may take as few as one instruction on some processors.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] A (non-recursive) mutex is either **locked** or unlocked.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] When a task has locked the mutex, all other tasks must wait for the mutex to be unlocked by its *owner* - the original thread.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] A task may set a timeout on its wait for a mutex.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] There are several well-known problems with mutex based designs such as priority inversion and deadlocks.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] In priority inversion a high priority task waits because a low priority task has a mutex, but the lower priority task is not given CPU time to finish its work.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] A typical solution is to have the task that owns a mutex 'inherit' the priority of the highest waiting task.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] But this simple approach gets more complex when there are multiple levels of waiting: task *A* waits for a mutex locked by task *B*, which waits for a mutex locked by task *C*.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Handling multiple levels of inheritance causes other code to run in high priority context and thus can cause starvation of medium-priority threads.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] In a deadlock, two or more tasks lock mutex without timeouts and then wait forever for the other task's mutex, creating a cyclic dependency.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The simplest deadlock scenario occurs when two tasks alternately lock two mutex, but in the opposite order.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Deadlock is prevented by careful design.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The other approach to resource sharing is for tasks to send messages in an organized message passing scheme.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] In this paradigm, the resource is managed directly by only one task.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] When another task wants to interrogate or manipulate the resource, it sends a message to the managing task.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Although their real-time behavior is less crisp than semaphore systems, simple message-based systems avoid most protocol deadlock hazards, and are generally better-behaved than semaphore systems.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] However, problems like those of semaphores are possible.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Priority inversion can occur when a task is working on a low-priority message and ignores a higher-priority message (or a message originating indirectly from a high priority task) in its incoming message queue.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Protocol deadlocks can occur when two or more tasks wait for each other to send response messages.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Since an interrupt handler blocks the highest priority task from running, and since real-time operating systems are designed to keep thread latency to a minimum, interrupt handlers are typically kept as short as possible.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The interrupt handler defers all interaction with the hardware if possible; typically all that is necessary is to acknowledge or disable the interrupt (so that it won't occur again when the interrupt handler returns) and notify a task that work needs to be done.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] This can be done by unblocking a driver task through releasing a semaphore, setting a flag or sending a message.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] A scheduler often provides the ability to unblock a task from interrupt handler context.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] An OS maintains catalogues of objects it manages such as threads, mutexes, memory, and so on.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Updates to this catalogue must be strictly controlled.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, it can be problematic when an interrupt handler calls an OS function while the application is in the act of also doing so.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The OS function called from an interrupt handler could find the object database to be in an inconsistent state because of the application's update.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] There are two major approaches to deal with this problem: the unified architecture and the segmented architecture.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] RTOSs implementing the unified architecture solve the problem by simply disabling interrupts while the internal catalogue is updated.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The downside of this is that interrupt latency increases, potentially losing interrupts.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The segmented architecture does not make direct OS calls but delegates the OS related work to a separate handler.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] This handler runs at a higher priority than any thread but lower than the interrupt handlers.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The advantage of this architecture is that it adds very few cycles to interrupt latency.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] As a result, OSes which implement the segmented architecture are more predictable and can deal with higher interrupt rates compared to the unified architecture.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Similarly, the System Management Mode on x86 compatible hardware can take a lot of time before it returns control to the operating system.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Memory allocation is more critical in a real-time operating system than in other operating systems.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] First, for stability there cannot be memory leaks (memory that is allocated but not freed after use).
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The device should work indefinitely, without ever needing a reboot.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, dynamic memory allocation is frowned upon.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Whenever possible, all required memory allocation is specified statically at compile time.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Another reason to avoid dynamic memory allocation is memory fragmentation.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] With frequent allocation and releasing of small chunks of memory, a situation may occur where available memory is divided into several sections and the RTOS cannot allocate a large enough continuous block of memory, although there is enough free memory.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Secondly, speed of allocation is important.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] A standard memory allocation scheme scans a linked list of indeterminate length to find a suitable free memory block, which is unacceptable in a RTOS since memory allocation has to occur within a certain amount of time.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] Because mechanical disks have much longer and more unpredictable response times, swapping to disk files is not used for the same reasons as RAM allocation discussed above.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] The simple fixed-size-blocks algorithm works quite well for simple embedded systems because of its low overhead.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] While all RTOSes are able to run on microcontrollers they have ports for, some RTOSes like Zephyr are capable of abstracting even further a number of device drivers like External Flash, I2C devices or internal peripherals like UART commands and sleep modes.
[src:rt-thread/real-time-operating-system] This helps offload the need for a developer to create drivers and instead a set of APIs are given for unsupported drivers to be ported over while supported ones are ready for use within the application code.
[src:rt-thread/rt-thread] As of August 2020, RT-Thread was reported to be #3 on the list of RTOSes with the largest number of contributors (behind Zephyr and Mbed).
[src:rt-thread/rt-thread] In 2006, RT-Thread began as an open-source real-time operating system (RTOS) that is mainly written in the programming language C.
[src:rt-thread/rt-thread] In 2017, a second variant was released for resource-constrained microcontrollers; it needs a minimum of 3 kB flash memory or read-only memory (ROM) and 1.2 kB random-access memory (RAM).
[src:rt-thread/rt-thread] Also, RT-Thread's first variant was named *Standard*, and second variant was named *Nano*.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] In computing, a **task** is a unit of execution or a unit of work.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] The term is ambiguous; precise alternative terms include *process*, light-weight process, *thread* (for execution), *step*, *request*, or *query* (for work).
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] In the adjacent diagram, there are queues of incoming work to do and outgoing completed work, and a thread pool of threads to perform this work.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] Either the work units themselves or the threads that perform the work can be referred to as "tasks", and these can be referred to respectively as requests/responses/threads, incoming tasks/completed tasks/threads (as illustrated), or requests/responses/tasks.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] In the sense of "unit of execution", in some operating systems, a task is synonymous with a process, and in others with a thread.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] In non-interactive execution (batch processing), a task is a unit of execution within a job, with the task itself typically a process.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] The term "multitasking" primarily refers to the processing sense – multiple tasks *executing* at the same time – but has nuances of the work sense of multiple tasks being *performed* at the same time.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] In online systems, tasks most commonly correspond to a single *request* (in request–response architectures) or a *query* (in information retrieval), either a single stage of handling, or the whole system-wide handling.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] The term task in OS/360 through z/OS is roughly equivalent to light-weight process; the tasks in a job step share an address space.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] However, in MVS/ESA through z/OS, a task or Service Request Block (SRB) may have access to other address spaces via its access list.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] The term *task* is used in the Linux kernel (at least since v2.6.13, up to and including v4.8) to refer to a unit of execution, which may share various system resources with other tasks on the system.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] Depending on the level of sharing, the task may be regarded as a conventional thread or process.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] Tasks are brought into existence using the `clone()` system call, where a user can specify the desired level of resource sharing.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] The term was popularized with the introduction of OS/360 (announced 1964), which featured Multiprogramming with a Fixed number of Tasks (MFT) and Multiprogramming with a Variable number of Tasks (MVT).
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] In this case tasks were identified with light-weight processes, a job consisted of a number of tasks, and, later, tasks could have sub-tasks (in modern terminology, child processes).
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] Today the term "task" is used very ambiguously.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] For example, the Windows Task Manager manages (running) *processes*, while Windows Task Scheduler schedules *programs* to execute in future, what is traditionally known as a job scheduler, and uses the `.job` extension.
[src:rt-thread/task-computing] By contrast, the term "task queue" is commonly used in the sense of "units of work".
